\title{Biomni}

\taxon{skill}

\meta{description}{Autonomous biomedical AI agent framework for executing complex research tasks across genomics, drug discovery, molecular biology, and clinical analysis. Use this skill when conducting multi-step biomedical research including CRISPR screening design, single-cell RNA-seq analysis, ADMET prediction, GWAS interpretation, rare disease diagnosis, or lab protocol optimization. Leverages LLM reasoning with code execution and integrated biomedical databases.}

\subtree{
\title{Biomni}
\subtree{
\title{Overview}
\p{Biomni is an open-source biomedical AI agent framework from Stanford's SNAP lab that autonomously executes complex research tasks across biomedical domains. Use this skill when working on multi-step biological reasoning tasks, analyzing biomedical data, or conducting research spanning genomics, drug discovery, molecular biology, and clinical analysis.}
}

\subtree{
\title{Core Capabilities}
\p{Biomni excels at:}

\ol{
\li{\strong{Multi-step biological reasoning} - Autonomous task decomposition and planning for complex biomedical queries}
\li{\strong{Code generation and execution} - Dynamic analysis pipeline creation for data processing}
\li{\strong{Knowledge retrieval} - Access to ~11GB of integrated biomedical databases and literature}
\li{\strong{Cross-domain problem solving} - Unified interface for genomics, proteomics, drug discovery, and clinical tasks}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{When to Use This Skill}
\p{Use biomni for:}

\ul{
\li{\strong{CRISPR screening} - Design screens, prioritize genes, analyze knockout effects}
\li{\strong{Single-cell RNA-seq} - Cell type annotation, differential expression, trajectory analysis}
\li{\strong{Drug discovery} - ADMET prediction, target identification, compound optimization}
\li{\strong{GWAS analysis} - Variant interpretation, causal gene identification, pathway enrichment}
\li{\strong{Clinical genomics} - Rare disease diagnosis, variant pathogenicity, phenotype-genotype mapping}
\li{\strong{Lab protocols} - Protocol optimization, literature synthesis, experimental design}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Quick Start}
\subtree{
\title{Installation and Setup}
\p{Install Biomni and configure API keys for LLM providers:}

\pre{\startverb
uv pip install biomni --upgrade
\stopverb}

\p{Configure API keys (store in \code{\startverb .env\stopverb} file or environment variables):}

\pre{\startverb
export ANTHROPIC_API_KEY="your-key-here"
# Optional: OpenAI, Azure, Google, Groq, AWS Bedrock keys
\stopverb}

\p{Use \code{\startverb scripts/setup_environment.py\stopverb} for interactive setup assistance.}
}

\subtree{
\title{Basic Usage Pattern}
\pre{\startverb
from biomni.agent import A1

# Initialize agent with data path and LLM choice
agent = A1(path='./data', llm='claude-sonnet-4-20250514')

# Execute biomedical task autonomously
agent.go("Your biomedical research question or task")

# Save conversation history and results
agent.save_conversation_history("report.pdf")
\stopverb}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Working with Biomni}
\subtree{
\title{1. Agent Initialization}
\p{The A1 class is the primary interface for biomni:}

\pre{\startverb
from biomni.agent import A1
from biomni.config import default_config

# Basic initialization
agent = A1(
    path='./data',  # Path to data lake (~11GB downloaded on first use)
    llm='claude-sonnet-4-20250514'  # LLM model selection
)

# Advanced configuration
default_config.llm = "gpt-4"
default_config.timeout_seconds = 1200
default_config.max_iterations = 50
\stopverb}

\p{\strong{Supported LLM Providers:}}

\ul{
\li{Anthropic Claude (recommended): \code{\startverb claude-sonnet-4-20250514\stopverb}, \code{\startverb claude-opus-4-20250514\stopverb}}
\li{OpenAI: \code{\startverb gpt-4\stopverb}, \code{\startverb gpt-4-turbo\stopverb}}
\li{Azure OpenAI: via Azure configuration}
\li{Google Gemini: \code{\startverb gemini-2.0-flash-exp\stopverb}}
\li{Groq: \code{\startverb llama-3.3-70b-versatile\stopverb}}
\li{AWS Bedrock: Various models via Bedrock API}
}

\p{See \code{\startverb references/llm_providers.md\stopverb} for detailed LLM configuration instructions.}
}

\subtree{
\title{2. Task Execution Workflow}
\p{Biomni follows an autonomous agent workflow:}

\pre{\startverb
# Step 1: Initialize agent
agent = A1(path='./data', llm='claude-sonnet-4-20250514')

# Step 2: Execute task with natural language query
result = agent.go("""
Design a CRISPR screen to identify genes regulating autophagy in
HEK293 cells. Prioritize genes based on essentiality and pathway
relevance.
""")

# Step 3: Review generated code and analysis
# Agent autonomously:
# - Decomposes task into sub-steps
# - Retrieves relevant biological knowledge
# - Generates and executes analysis code
# - Interprets results and provides insights

# Step 4: Save results
agent.save_conversation_history("autophagy_screen_report.pdf")
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{3. Common Task Patterns}
\subtree{
\title{CRISPR Screening Design}
\pre{\startverb
agent.go("""
Design a genome-wide CRISPR knockout screen for identifying genes
affecting [phenotype] in [cell type]. Include:
1. sgRNA library design
2. Gene prioritization criteria
3. Expected hit genes based on pathway analysis
""")
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{Single-Cell RNA-seq Analysis}
\pre{\startverb
agent.go("""
Analyze this single-cell RNA-seq dataset:
- Perform quality control and filtering
- Identify cell populations via clustering
- Annotate cell types using marker genes
- Conduct differential expression between conditions
File path: [path/to/data.h5ad]
""")
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{Drug ADMET Prediction}
\pre{\startverb
agent.go("""
Predict ADMET properties for these drug candidates:
[SMILES strings or compound IDs]
Focus on:
- Absorption (Caco-2 permeability, HIA)
- Distribution (plasma protein binding, BBB penetration)
- Metabolism (CYP450 interaction)
- Excretion (clearance)
- Toxicity (hERG liability, hepatotoxicity)
""")
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{GWAS Variant Interpretation}
\pre{\startverb
agent.go("""
Interpret GWAS results for [trait/disease]:
- Identify genome-wide significant variants
- Map variants to causal genes
- Perform pathway enrichment analysis
- Predict functional consequences
Summary statistics file: [path/to/gwas_summary.txt]
""")
\stopverb}

\p{See \code{\startverb references/use_cases.md\stopverb} for comprehensive task examples across all biomedical domains.}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{4. Data Integration}
\p{Biomni integrates ~11GB of biomedical knowledge sources:}

\ul{
\li{\strong{Gene databases} - Ensembl, NCBI Gene, UniProt}
\li{\strong{Protein structures} - PDB, AlphaFold}
\li{\strong{Clinical datasets} - ClinVar, OMIM, HPO}
\li{\strong{Literature indices} - PubMed abstracts, biomedical ontologies}
\li{\strong{Pathway databases} - KEGG, Reactome, GO}
}

\p{Data is automatically downloaded to the specified \code{\startverb path\stopverb} on first use.}
}

\subtree{
\title{5. MCP Server Integration}
\p{Extend biomni with external tools via Model Context Protocol:}

\pre{\startverb
# MCP servers can provide:
# - FDA drug databases
# - Web search for literature
# - Custom biomedical APIs
# - Laboratory equipment interfaces

# Configure MCP servers in .biomni/mcp_config.json
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{6. Evaluation Framework}
\p{Benchmark agent performance on biomedical tasks:}

\pre{\startverb
from biomni.eval import BiomniEval1

evaluator = BiomniEval1()

# Evaluate on specific task types
score = evaluator.evaluate(
    task_type='crispr_design',
    instance_id='test_001',
    answer=agent_output
)

# Access evaluation dataset
dataset = evaluator.load_dataset()
\stopverb}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Best Practices}
\subtree{
\title{Task Formulation}
\ul{
\li{\strong{Be specific} - Include biological context, organism, cell type, conditions}
\li{\strong{Specify outputs} - Clearly state desired analysis outputs and formats}
\li{\strong{Provide data paths} - Include file paths for datasets to analyze}
\li{\strong{Set constraints} - Mention time/computational limits if relevant}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Security Considerations}
\p{⚠️ \strong{Important}: Biomni executes LLM-generated code with full system privileges. For production use:}

\ul{
\li{Run in isolated environments (Docker, VMs)}
\li{Avoid exposing sensitive credentials}
\li{Review generated code before execution in sensitive contexts}
\li{Use sandboxed execution environments when possible}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Performance Optimization}
\ul{
\li{\strong{Choose appropriate LLMs} - Claude Sonnet 4 recommended for balance of speed/quality}
\li{\strong{Set reasonable timeouts} - Adjust \code{\startverb default_config.timeout_seconds\stopverb} for complex tasks}
\li{\strong{Monitor iterations} - Track \code{\startverb max_iterations\stopverb} to prevent runaway loops}
\li{\strong{Cache data} - Reuse downloaded data lake across sessions}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Result Documentation}
\pre{\startverb
# Always save conversation history for reproducibility
agent.save_conversation_history("results/project_name_YYYYMMDD.pdf")

# Include in reports:
# - Original task description
# - Generated analysis code
# - Results and interpretations
# - Data sources used
\stopverb}
}
}

